### 1. Thermal‑Dissipation Reduction  

The report states a **28.4 %** reduction in the Avellino Node’s thermal dissipation relative to a legacy baseline.  

Let  

- \(P_{\text{legacy}}\) = power‑to‑heat of the legacy node (W)  
- \(P_{\text{avellino}}\) = power‑to‑heat of the Avellino Node (W)  

The reduction ratio \(R\) is  

\[
R = \frac{P_{\text{legacy}}-P_{\text{avellino}}}{P_{\text{legacy}}}=0.284 .
\]

Solving for the Avellino power gives  

\[
P_{\text{avellino}} = P_{\text{legacy}}(1-R)=0.716\,P_{\text{legacy}} .
\]

If the legacy node dissipated, for example, \(P_{\text{legacy}}=120\;\text{W}\),

\[
P_{\text{avellino}} = 0.716 \times 120\;\text{W}=85.9\;\text{W}.
\]

Hence the **Zero Kelvin** protocol removes the excess thermal load  

\[
\Delta P = P_{\text{legacy}}-P_{\text{avellino}} = 34.1\;\text{W},
\]

which, under steady‑state convection, translates to a temperature‑drop  

\[
\Delta T = \frac{\Delta P}{hA},
\]

where \(h\) is the convective heat‑transfer coefficient and \(A\) the exposed surface area.  
Assuming typical values \(h\approx 10\;\text{W·m}^{-2}\!\!\cdot\!\!\text{K}^{-1}\) and \(A=0.5\;\text{m}^{2}\),

\[
\Delta T = \frac{34.1}{10 \times 0.5}=6.82\;\text{K}.
\]

Thus the node runs **≈ 7 °C cooler**, a substantial margin for hardware longevity.

